            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this stair calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This stair calculator is designed for builders, carpenters, and
                DIY homeowners. It takes your floor‑to‑floor height and target
                step dimensions, then finds a stair layout that:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Uses an integer number of risers and treads</li>
                <li>
                  Keeps riser height and tread depth within typical residential
                  code ranges
                </li>
                <li>
                  Checks the comfort rule \(2R + T\) and approximate headroom
                </li>
                <li>
                  Provides practical stringer layout values for plumb and seat
                  cuts
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Number of risers</strong></p>
                <p>We start from your total rise and target riser height:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ N_r =
                  \text{round}\left(\frac{H_\text{total}}{R_\text{target}}\right)
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>Then the actual riser height is:</p>
                <p>\[ R = \frac{H_\text{total}}{N_r} \]</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>2. Number of treads and total run</strong></p>
                <p>For a straight stair:</p>
                <p>\[ N_t = N_r - 1 \]</p>
                <p>\[ L_\text{run} = N_t \times T \]</p>
                <p>where \(T\) is the tread depth (run).</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>3. Stair angle and stringer length</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \theta =
                  \tan^{-1}\left(\frac{H_\text{total}}{L_\text{run}}\right) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ L_\text{stringer} = \sqrt{H_\text{total}^2 +
                  L_\text{run}^2} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>4. Comfort rule (2R + T)</strong></p>
                <p>A common guideline for comfortable stairs is:</p>
                <p>\[ 2R + T \approx 24\text{–}25\ \text{inches} \]</p>
                <p>
                  The calculator shows the value of \(2R + T\) so you can see
                  how your design compares.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Typical residential stair guidelines (non‑binding)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Riser height: 7&quot;–7.75&quot; (178–197&nbsp;mm)</li>
                <li>Tread depth: 10&quot;–11&quot; (254–280&nbsp;mm)</li>
                <li>Stair angle: roughly 30°–38°</li>
                <li>Headroom: at least 80&quot; (2032&nbsp;mm)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong>Always check your local building code</strong> (IRC,
                IBC, or local amendments). This tool is for planning and
                estimation only and does not replace a stamped design or code
                review.
              </p>

              <h2>Step‑by‑step: laying out a stair stringer</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Measure the finished floor‑to‑floor height (including subfloor
                  and finish materials).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter the total rise and your preferred riser height and tread
                  depth.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Calculate stair”</strong> to get the exact
                  riser height, tread depth, and number of steps.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Set your framing square with the calculated rise on one leg
                  and run on the other.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Mark each step along the 2×12 using the square, following the
                  stringer layout instructions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cut the plumb cut at the top and the seat cut at the bottom as
                  indicated.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This version assumes a straight stair with no intermediate
                  landing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Headroom is approximated using your available horizontal run;
                  complex framing conditions are not modeled.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For commercial or multi‑flight stairs, consult a structural
                  professional.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
